{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9901,"record_hash":"sha256:b39e68e1af4d78bceef4b8844b14923c19c4f577111130fb46c039bc25d1b386","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:36:16.939Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Short version: your plan holds up, but I’d sharpen the mental model.\n\nThis is not “resume the old session.” That only works inside one provider. GitButler’s lane is **portable reference/catch-up**: discover prior work for this branch/change/review, inspect an outline, hydrate the useful windows, then let the new agent continue.\n\nI updated the notes here: [handoff-design.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md>)\n\n**What Prior Art Says**\nClaude Code and Copilot CLI both have strong native resume UX: continue latest, picker, resume by id/name, rename, export, branch/fork. Claude’s picker has branch/worktree filtering, which is very relevant. Copilot’s `/chronicle` is the closest match to “ask my session history what happened.” Sources: [Claude sessions](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/sessions), [Copilot CLI session data](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/how-tos/copilot-cli/use-copilot-cli/chronicle), [Copilot session data model](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/concepts/agents/copilot-cli/chronicle).\n\nThe big lesson: raw logs are truth, derived summaries/search/indexes are conveniences. Copilot stores full local session files plus a derived SQLite-ish store, and can reindex from truth. That maps neatly to GitMeta truth plus optional derived query/read surfaces.\n\nLangGraph and Copilot SDK reinforce stable session/checkpoint IDs. But I would not copy their full checkpoint model yet. We already have capture turns as durable checkpoints of observed work. Source: [LangGraph persistence](https://langchain-5e9cc07a.mintlify.app/oss/python/langgraph/persistence), [Copilot SDK persistence](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/how-tos/copilot-sdk/use-copilot-sdk/session-persistence).\n\nMCP’s tools/resources/prompts split is useful: expose session/timeline data like resources, use tools for bounded reads, and maybe a prompt/skill for the catch-up workflow. Source: [MCP server concepts](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/learn/server-concepts).\n\nAider and Continue support the same shape: compact orientation first, then targeted reads. Aider’s repo map is a good analogy: don’t dump the whole repo, give an outline that helps the model choose what to inspect. Sources: [Aider repo map](https://aider.chat/docs/repomap.html), [Continue context providers](https://docs.continue.dev/customize/custom-providers).\n\n**What I’d Change**\nI’d keep our first implementation boring:\n\n1. Make `agentlog sessions` return a useful outline, not just keys.\n2. Add `agentlog timeline <session-key>` for cheap turn-level inspection.\n3. Add `agentlog related-detail ...` for bounded transcript hydration.\n4. Later, add a skill or MCP prompt that teaches agents the catch-up sequence.\n\nI would not start with a magic `handoff` command, persistent generated summaries, SLSA-style provenance, or full transcript dumping. Those are seductive and mostly the wrong kind of impressive. The good feature is: “a tired agent can continue safely in five minutes.”","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:36:16.939Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}